Rating: 4
It's almost shocking, how easy this is and how perfectly it always turns out! It takes literally 5 minutes to get the chicken ready to roast, and 5 minutes to carve things up at the end of the cooking time. It's tough to find a chicken as small as the one called for, so I just get what they have at the grocery store and guesstimate on the cooking time. It helps to use a meat thermometer and to watch the little popup thingy most commercial chickens have these days. I think it took about 90 minutes for the most recent one. Most recently, I added potatoes and carrots to the bottom of the roasting pan, as another reviewer suggested. The potatoes were fine - nothing really all that special but it was an easy way to cook them. The carrots, however - they were blackened in places and looked limp and not at all attractive... but holy cow they tasted DIVINE. My teenage son refused to try them because he insisted they were burned. I made him try just one - and he wolfed down as many as we'd left for him (the family was fighting over them). Next time we'll probably skip the potatoes and put a lot more carrots in the pan. The drippings make a very nice gravy as well. You can move the chicken to another platter while it rests, and deglaze the pan, then just add a simple flour/water mix to the drippings for thickening. Might be slightly salty depending on how much salt you used on the bird, but it wasn't unpalatably so.

