Rating: 4
To the Cook from Colorado, yes, table salt is sort of more salty than kosher. Kosher or sea salt have bigger grains therefore a teaspoon of kosher or sea actually has less density than a teaspoon of table salt. Its just like with sugar...you need more raw sugar than you would confectioners, etc etc. That said, this is still the very best roast chicken I have ever made/eaten, even though it makes my smoke detector go off.

Rating: 4
Wonderful, easy recipe. I was so worried I'd have trouble with smoke and spitting grease, especially since I have an old, dirty oven. But I just put some sliced potatoes and carrots in the pan, and put a veggie steamer on top of that to hold the chicken above the veggies. (My turkey roaster rack was WAY too big.) I used a 4.5 lb farm raised chicken, cooked it for 80 minutes. To prep, filled a tablespoon with coarse kosher salt and "rained" it on the chicken, it was just the right amount of salt. I didn't buy fresh thyme, just sprinkled a little bit of dried thyme on top of the salt. I put the chicken on the bottom oven rack. Didn't open the oven for 80 minutes until it was done. When letting the chicken rest, I couldn't find my baster so I just ladled some of the juices on top of the chicken. No butter was necessary but the mustard was a nice condiment. It served 4 with just a little bit left over. The white meat was juicy, the skin was crispy, it was truly the best roast chicken I have ever had. Everyone thought I worked so hard...15 minutes of prep, 80 minutes of cook time = so easy and delicious!

