Rating: 4
Let me just start off with saying I'm a five-ingredient girl, two of which are always salt and pepper. So when my sister recommended this wholeheartedly, I went for it. I have a very sensitive smoke detector, so I went all out. Opened the kitchen window, left the sliding door 1/4 open, turned on the ceiling fan. I lined the bottom rack with heavy duty foil. For roasting, I used a heavy duty cast iron pan with a small toaster rack to prop up the chicken and collect all that juice for the gravy later. I also sliced up some small potatoes to help soak up a bit of the grease as recommended (to keep splatters and smoking to a minimum). Took note and really wiped that bird down dry before liberally salting (using table salt) and a few dashes of pepper. Did not truss. Put that baby in on the second to lowest rack and turned up the heat (450 degrees for an hour) -which was a good thing, because it was 12 degrees outside (ha) and it was getting chilly in the house. I did peek in the oven once and there was definitely smoke billowing inside (alot), but the precautions I took, thanks to everyone's suggestion, meant my smoke alart stayed silent. Oh my goodness - hands down, simple, juicy and oh so good. This is a keeper! Did not add the mustard, did not slather the meat with butter (though I was dearly tempted). Yum, will make this again and again.

