Rating: 4
I'm adding my second review of this recipe in order to respond to some other reviewers negative results. (Funny, I almost feel compelled to defend this great roasting technique.) 1) Kosher salt and other coarse salts can vary greatly in terms of "saltiness." For example, ordinary table salt weighs 10 oz. per cup; Morton's Coarse Kosher Salt weighs 7.7 oz. per cup; and Diamond Crystal Kosher Salt weighs 5 oz. per cup. (The variation is due to the differing sizes of the kosher salt grains. The size of the grains affects the saltiness you perceive.) Therefore, table salt tastes saltier than Morton's which tastes saltier than Diamond brand. If you are using Kosher or Sea Salt, know thy salt. It will make a difference. I find that I prefer the less salty Diamond brand in this recipe. 2) The smoke in the kitchen is most likely due to the spattering of the fat from the browning skin onto the heating element. Move the rack in your oven down. 3) Those who really hated the dish seem to have violated the one cardinal rule to making this recipe a success. DRY the chicken. If you add moisture to the outside of the chicken, by squeezing lemon onto the outside of the chicken or adding other liquids, you end up steaming the chicken rather than roasting it and will not get a good result.

