Rating: 4
Sometimes the simplest dishes are the best. Over the years, I've roasted many chickens. I've made recipes which involved starting the chicken on its breast side down and then turning it over. Recipes where chickens were brined, tented with foil, basted, or rubbed with a variety of oils or butter. Recipes that involved turning the temperature up and down during the course of cooking. But this set it and forget it method made a moist and perfectly roasted chicken. (Not to mention allowed me to focus my efforts on the side dishes). The high temperature and thoroughly drying the chicken... along with the trussing, sealed all the juices in. Suprisingly, basting the chicken with the thyme infused juices during its 15 minute setting time, allowed the flavor to penetrate well. I plan on experimenting with this recipe, in terms of seasoning under the skin or the cavity with various herbs and spices. But, I will keep the cooking method the same. Delicious!

